Namaste Rajarshi,
 
It is not like the two definitions are always off by a month. They actually match in most years.
 
According to the definition used today, Margasira month starts when Sun and Moon conjoin in Vrischika raasi, i.e. Moon is in Vrischika raasi at the end of Amaavaasyaa tithi when a new lunar month begins. If you look at the Pournima of such a month in the last 3 years, Moon was indeed in Rohini/Mrigasira or in Mrigasira/Aardra on the Pournima day. The standard definition results in the same reckoning most of the times. This year happens to be a border year where the two definitions are mis-aligned by one month.
 
I believe the error in reckoning came in during the last millennium or so. The birth tithis of gods, rishis and yogis noted from the ancient times (e.g. Lord Rama's birth on Chaitra Sukla Navami, Dattatreya's birth on Margasira Pournima etc) must have been noted down using the "correct definition". It is upto us now to iron out the correct definition now.
 
*        *        *
 
